THE Deputy Inspector General of Police in charge of South-West Zone, Johnson Kokumo, on Tuesday held a meeting with police officers in the Ogun State Command over the threat to embark on strike. The DIG, who arrived the state police command, Eleweran, Abeokuta at 1.22pm, went straight to hold a meeting with the policemen with a view to persuading them to shelve their planned strike. Kokumo reminded the policemen of their duties as the lead security agency in the country that is saddled with the responsibility of protecting the citizens. He said, “As officers, we have to observe and obey the law. We have to ensure we use our power within the confine of the law. “Conduct yourself professionally. Let there be a healthy respect of the rights of the citizens, we are to protect. “We want to see a Nigeria Police Force that is people-friendly, professional and has respect for the rights of the citizens. “The public will then see us as their friends when we do these.” He said the government was ready to provide all the requirements needed to carry out the duties professionally. Earlier, the state Commissioner of Police, Lanre Bankole, assured the DIG of complete loyalty to the Nigeria Police Force adding, that the command will be professional in discharging its duties. He said, “I want to assure you that no member of this command will be involved in any form of planned strike action. “I am sure that I am speaking the minds of the officers who are here including the generality of members of the Nigeria Police Force, Ogun State Command.” Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com